1
00:00:00,537 --> 00:00:14,691
Namo tassa bhagavato harahto samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and fully Self-Enlightened One.

2
00:00:14,750 --> 00:00:20,457
So this retreat is the beginning of our little season which lasts about three-quarters of a year.

3
00:00:21,838 --> 00:00:29,986
So I suppose I'd better say something especially inspiring to kick off the season.

4
00:00:30,946 --> 00:00:43,359
That exercise, that standing exercise that we do, just to get across those particular qualities, that's the platform of your meditation.

5
00:00:43,459 --> 00:00:50,106
Those qualities are what you first of all develop before you bring in the inquiry.

6
00:00:51,487 --> 00:00:55,692
So the seven factors, right awareness.

7
00:00:55,712 --> 00:00:57,274
Awareness is just...

8
00:00:59,531 --> 00:01:00,512
Well, it's just being here, isn't it?

9
00:01:01,475 --> 00:01:03,798
Just like, it's just being here.

10
00:01:04,039 --> 00:01:10,367
You know, awareness is all the... People put a sort of a mystical turn on it.

11
00:01:11,168 --> 00:01:11,930
But it's quite natural.

12
00:01:12,010 --> 00:01:13,332
Animals have it.

13
00:01:13,412 --> 00:01:13,993
Everybody has.

14
00:01:15,015 --> 00:01:15,977
You're just being here.

15
00:01:19,522 --> 00:01:19,742
Yeah.

16
00:01:20,022 --> 00:01:23,388
What turns it into right awareness, of course, is what it is you're aware of.

17
00:01:24,149 --> 00:01:26,371
That's the difference.

18
00:01:26,391 --> 00:01:27,513
And then there's...

19
00:01:27,712 --> 00:01:29,454
these qualities of calmness.

20
00:01:32,317 --> 00:01:36,543
So you always begin our meditation by establishing that sense of calmness.

21
00:01:36,884 --> 00:01:41,849
See, the body, calm body, still body, that's about the easiest.

22
00:01:42,170 --> 00:01:43,450
That's the easiest thing we can get.

23
00:01:44,371 --> 00:01:46,775
Just to bring the body to us, to a stillness.

24
00:01:48,197 --> 00:01:49,838
And that immediately affects the mind.

25
00:01:50,980 --> 00:01:56,286
Because, remember, in Buddhism the mind is, the mind and the body

26
00:01:56,704 --> 00:02:10,419
are not, what's the word, they're entwined, they dissolve the one into the other.

27
00:02:11,319 --> 00:02:21,370
When the Buddha talks about the body, he's not normally talking about the physical body that we know, such as your nails or your bones.

28
00:02:21,389 --> 00:02:26,155
He's talking about the sentient body, what you actually feel in the body.

29
00:02:28,462 --> 00:02:30,466
And actually that belongs to the mind.

30
00:02:31,225 --> 00:02:35,131
It's where the body and mind meet, that point of contact.

31
00:02:36,913 --> 00:02:47,467
So as soon as you relax the physical frame, the sort of heavy physical nature, it immediately begins to relax this inner body of the mind.

32
00:02:49,269 --> 00:02:51,271
And that brings about a stillness.

33
00:02:51,953 --> 00:02:56,157
Normally speaking we do it by lying down, and then very shortly fall asleep.

34
00:02:57,067 --> 00:03:00,352
which isn't really insightful meditation.

35
00:03:01,973 --> 00:03:10,586
It's only, you've got to somehow establish that calmness that you would normally get just lying down and relaxing, but to keep the wakefulness.

36
00:03:11,045 --> 00:03:15,072
That's the problem.

37
00:03:15,092 --> 00:03:17,836
And that's the sense of Pasadi.

38
00:03:17,855 --> 00:03:25,385
Now this Pasadi actually has a connection with curiosity.

39
00:03:26,546 --> 00:03:30,973
And curiosity is that quality within us that wants to know.

40
00:03:31,014 --> 00:03:39,026
And if the calmness isn't there, then what happens is it gets very excited, and then the mind starts wandering.

41
00:03:40,247 --> 00:03:42,110
So these two things balance themselves.

42
00:03:42,311 --> 00:03:54,310
But if you try to go into a meditation with just that sense of wanting to know, you often find yourself getting just excited about it.

43
00:03:54,728 --> 00:03:57,931
brings in a sort of wrong energy, a restlessness.

44
00:03:57,951 --> 00:04:00,554
So if you have this platform of calmness, you see.

45
00:04:01,014 --> 00:04:04,758
So that's why we use the breath just to bring this sense of calmness.

46
00:04:06,200 --> 00:04:10,985
And when that's there, it's as though you awaken that wanting to know.

47
00:04:12,288 --> 00:04:16,052
So if you're looking at this carpet, for instance, and just relaxing your eye on it, you see.

48
00:04:17,312 --> 00:04:18,814
And then this little bug walks across.

49
00:04:20,036 --> 00:04:22,738
And immediately the curiosity comes.

50
00:04:22,759 --> 00:04:23,519
It's not as though

51
00:04:23,922 --> 00:04:26,185
You have to work at curiosity, it's quite natural.

52
00:04:28,048 --> 00:04:32,293
But if the calmness is not there, or if your attention is somewhere else, you don't see it.

53
00:04:32,714 --> 00:04:38,824
You know, I think about watching, I think it's a football match, and they put a gorilla going across the pitch and nobody sees it.

54
00:04:39,064 --> 00:04:41,107
You know that one.

55
00:04:41,127 --> 00:04:44,793
Basketball, is it?

56
00:04:45,494 --> 00:04:47,175
That's too much concentration, you see.

57
00:04:48,156 --> 00:04:53,305
So you don't want too much concentration, you want enough to see things arising and passing away, you see.

58
00:04:56,086 --> 00:05:06,158
Then there's that sense of steadiness of attention, which I think is a much better phrase than concentration, because when you say concentration, it brings a tightness to it.

59
00:05:06,298 --> 00:05:12,406
I think it brings reminds of school and stuff like that, or a knitted brow and that sort of thing.

60
00:05:12,565 --> 00:05:15,449
But actually, it's just steadiness of attention.

61
00:05:15,829 --> 00:05:24,220
Now, when I first began teaching, I taught it in the Eastern Method, which is really about effort and concentration.

62
00:05:25,211 --> 00:05:28,875
And I just found people exhausting themselves.

63
00:05:29,175 --> 00:05:37,524
And it was only later I realized, actually, what motivates us more is this sense of inquiry, this sense of curiosity.

64
00:05:37,985 --> 00:05:40,466
And that when it comes to energy, if anything, we've got too much of it.

65
00:05:41,507 --> 00:05:45,672
So I wouldn't worry too much about concentration.

66
00:05:46,452 --> 00:05:53,220
If you ask yourself, do you ever have problems with concentration when you're interested in something?

67
00:05:53,240 --> 00:05:53,699
You don't, do you?

68
00:05:54,406 --> 00:05:55,286
It's just natural.

69
00:05:55,447 --> 00:05:57,108
You just naturally want it.

70
00:05:57,348 --> 00:06:01,874
So often our practice is raising that interest.

71
00:06:02,154 --> 00:06:02,375
See?

72
00:06:02,615 --> 00:06:07,880
Raising the interest.

73
00:06:07,901 --> 00:06:11,004
And then there's this quality of equanimity.

74
00:06:11,966 --> 00:06:15,428
That's really, really important.

75
00:06:15,449 --> 00:06:19,834
Equanimity in the factors of enlightenment has these two qualities.

76
00:06:19,994 --> 00:06:22,336
It has a heart quality of

77
00:06:22,569 --> 00:06:32,281
not being attached to something, having no preference, not holding on to something.

78
00:06:33,624 --> 00:06:39,872
And it has a wisdom quality or a mental quality of not coming from a particular view or an opinion.

79
00:06:41,153 --> 00:06:47,560
So it's really a very deep concept about a position you take in life.

80
00:06:49,584 --> 00:06:52,307
Very relaxed, very much at ease with the way things are.

81
00:06:52,793 --> 00:07:18,901
not wanting them to be other than they are I mean I'm talking about the present moment so you don't find yourself in conflict with the world once we are in a situation and we see it as it is then potential always arises because time changes, changes everything there's no such thing as time, it's just this process of change so it's not as though when you walk into a situation

82
00:07:19,372 --> 00:07:23,458
that you accept it in that sort of resigned way, this is the way and I can't do anything.

83
00:07:23,958 --> 00:07:28,564
It's more in the sense of, this is the way it is, and then what can be done?

84
00:07:29,826 --> 00:07:34,492
But if you don't see it as it is, then you're always imposing something on that situation.

85
00:07:35,014 --> 00:07:37,055
As soon as you do that, you're in conflict.

86
00:07:37,076 --> 00:07:38,738
You want it to be other than it is, you see.

87
00:07:41,802 --> 00:07:43,504
And that's what we're learning in this meditation.

88
00:07:43,524 --> 00:07:48,331
We're learning just to let the body be the body, let the heart be the heart, let the mind be the mind.

89
00:07:49,915 --> 00:07:53,658
So if the body feels discomfort, you just let it feel discomfort.

90
00:07:55,300 --> 00:07:58,483
Most discomfort in meditation comes from mental states within the body.

91
00:07:59,024 --> 00:08:03,569
Heaviness, dullness, all those sorts of things.

92
00:08:03,588 --> 00:08:12,437
And if there's a pain comes in meditation, then you have to decide whether it's just something which is not important or something which is.

93
00:08:12,939 --> 00:08:16,502
So for instance, if you're getting pain in the back, it may be your posture's wrong.

94
00:08:16,523 --> 00:08:18,824
So you have to look at that and make sure your posture's correct.

95
00:08:19,312 --> 00:08:24,235
If the posture is correct, then it's probably some mental state caught up in there, some tension.

96
00:08:25,317 --> 00:08:26,699
Because that's what we realize, isn't it?

97
00:08:26,718 --> 00:08:33,043
That the mind deposits these turbulences in certain places in the body.

98
00:08:34,405 --> 00:08:40,971
That's why you feel anger in the chest, you feel grief in the chest, you feel fear in your stomach and things like that.

99
00:08:41,692 --> 00:08:44,234
There are certain places, you see, where it sort of deposits it.

100
00:08:45,335 --> 00:08:48,238
And often we're not aware of it at all in our daily lives.

101
00:08:48,590 --> 00:08:54,719
But suddenly when you sit, you suddenly get these funny feelings come up.

102
00:08:54,739 --> 00:09:03,091
But if you feel that, if there's a physical feeling, such as your knees, then obviously that's coming from the body, and you just have to be careful, that's all.

103
00:09:10,964 --> 00:09:16,032
So these factors, the awareness, which is a sort of governing factor,

104
00:09:16,770 --> 00:09:22,717
The Buddha goes as far as saying, if you get the right awareness, the rest of it just falls into place.

105
00:09:22,738 --> 00:09:23,979
You don't have to work at the others.

106
00:09:24,759 --> 00:09:28,945
That doesn't mean to say that we shouldn't be aware that sometimes things go wrong.

107
00:09:30,046 --> 00:09:34,431
So, if there's too much calmness, there's a tendency to sleep.

108
00:09:34,451 --> 00:09:36,433
So you've got to put effort in there.

109
00:09:36,453 --> 00:09:36,953
Keep awake.

110
00:09:37,634 --> 00:09:39,496
If there's too much effort, then it gets tight.

111
00:09:40,577 --> 00:09:43,000
And you find yourself getting restless.

112
00:09:43,020 --> 00:09:43,841
So then you have to calm yourself.

113
00:09:44,277 --> 00:09:51,125
So it's a case of juggling these states, you see, until you find yourself in a position of just general calmness, stillness of mind.

114
00:09:52,047 --> 00:09:56,933
And in a sense, we ought to try and do that within 5, 10, 15 minutes of a sitting.

115
00:09:58,576 --> 00:10:04,224
And what happens if you do that is you find this observation post.

116
00:10:04,244 --> 00:10:09,049
That's a phrase I get from Jnana Ponika.

117
00:10:09,070 --> 00:10:14,216
It still is the best book to read, The Heart of Buddhist Meditations.

118
00:10:15,445 --> 00:10:16,426
He was a German monk.

119
00:10:16,746 --> 00:10:20,392
He died quite a while back now.

120
00:10:20,412 --> 00:10:24,037
What you find is that this awareness, it withdraws, doesn't it?

121
00:10:24,677 --> 00:10:30,264
It finds this place above, within the psychophysical organism.

122
00:10:31,986 --> 00:10:32,427
Am I correct?

123
00:10:34,429 --> 00:10:36,352
Not vigorously pleased.

124
00:10:36,373 --> 00:10:37,794
So you're finding this place, you see.

125
00:10:38,235 --> 00:10:43,022
Now this is the spiritual point, you see, because from this place

126
00:10:43,693 --> 00:11:13,413
you can observe what arises in the body whether it's pleasant or unpleasant you can observe what's arising in the heart in terms of its emotional mood states and although it's difficult you've got to be really sharp you can see thoughts but you can definitely catch images so it's a very privileged space that you find when this awareness abstracts itself from that psychophysical organism

127
00:11:14,018 --> 00:11:18,663
And our job is to maintain that as best we can.

128
00:11:20,384 --> 00:11:22,567
And just to keep watching, just to keep watching.

129
00:11:23,607 --> 00:11:31,936
And our faith, you see, the trust, is that this awareness is itself Buddha nature, is itself the intelligence.

130
00:11:31,956 --> 00:11:34,698
And it will come to know, it will liberate itself.

131
00:11:35,359 --> 00:11:38,722
As soon as you try, it's coming from some other center.

132
00:11:38,942 --> 00:11:43,047
It's coming from this, I know, this is the way it should be, is it?

133
00:11:43,600 --> 00:11:47,325
And as soon as that happens, we're completely deluded.

134
00:11:47,345 --> 00:11:56,317
And this essence within us, this consciousness, this awareness, is constantly screaming, get that meditator out of the way.

135
00:11:58,201 --> 00:11:58,961
See?

136
00:11:58,981 --> 00:12:08,916
And you get the meditator out of the way by observing whatever is arising and passing away in that calm way.

137
00:12:12,304 --> 00:12:19,975
Now as you're observing things, so pain comes up in your knee, there's always this reaction to something which is unpleasant.

138
00:12:21,177 --> 00:12:26,365
So you're always watching this reaction because it's drawing you into a relationship, a wrong relationship.

139
00:12:27,226 --> 00:12:32,774
So a mood or emotion which is nasty, some sort of fear, some sort of anxiety, depression.

140
00:12:33,475 --> 00:12:36,100
You're always watching that, not wanting to go there.

141
00:12:37,282 --> 00:12:41,467
And remember the two suppressive forces are aversion and fear.

142
00:12:42,089 --> 00:12:43,711
That's what's keeping things away from us.

143
00:12:44,692 --> 00:12:49,597
So by turning on to that reaction, you're getting in contact with this aversion, this fear.

144
00:12:51,139 --> 00:13:01,732
And it's allowing that to die away, that we're able to find that space, that courage really, to face the original problem.

145
00:13:01,753 --> 00:13:11,725
And as you face the original problem, which is this nasty emotion coming, which is normally felt as a feeling in the body, you're actually allowing it to exhaust itself.

146
00:13:12,514 --> 00:13:15,437
It's just, all it is, it's an energy.

147
00:13:16,538 --> 00:13:20,222
It's the mind which puts a label on it.

148
00:13:20,243 --> 00:13:26,830
So when you get something like fear or depression, you see, the mind suddenly says, depression, fear, so you get this pushing away, not wanting.

149
00:13:27,330 --> 00:13:28,652
You wait for that to die away.

150
00:13:28,991 --> 00:13:37,821
And as that original feeling starts coming up, you see, and you draw your attention into it, it loses that definition.

151
00:13:38,020 --> 00:13:41,745
It just becomes heaviness or sickliness or, yeah,

152
00:13:42,350 --> 00:13:45,634
And at that point, you see, all you're doing is observing energy.

153
00:13:45,833 --> 00:13:47,096
You're in a flow of energy.

154
00:13:48,017 --> 00:13:49,339
And this is a turbulence.

155
00:13:49,538 --> 00:13:52,422
And if you just give it enough time, it exhausts itself.

156
00:13:53,644 --> 00:13:55,706
And that's one set of conditioning gone.

157
00:13:55,725 --> 00:13:59,110
And then you think, no more fear, no more depression.

158
00:13:59,350 --> 00:14:01,192
Oh, very foolish.

159
00:14:02,995 --> 00:14:04,197
Next morning you wake up with more.

160
00:14:04,636 --> 00:14:07,039
And that's what can be a little depressing.

161
00:14:08,422 --> 00:14:10,904
In fact, there's a lot of this gung down there, you see.

162
00:14:11,424 --> 00:14:40,774
but what you discover is that by creating a right attitude towards it somehow it takes the edge of suffering out and what you begin to realize is that the pain which is coming the discomfort which is coming is not actually suffering it's always that relationship that's the suffering and when you identify with that relationship of wanting and not wanting that is the suffering

163
00:14:41,682 --> 00:14:58,376
as long as we can maintain the position of the objective observer the objective feeler, the objective experiencer even in the most disgusting and awful turbulences it's not the same as actually suffering which is when you become it, right?

164
00:14:58,397 --> 00:15:10,407
to observe depression is not the same as being depressed to observe fear is not the same as being fearful and it's catching that distinction, you see and realizing that this position

165
00:15:11,062 --> 00:15:40,647
of the observer the feeler is a liberation in itself a liberation in itself now when it comes to the pleasant side see the indulgence brings us shall we say a sense of nibbana

166
00:15:41,369 --> 00:15:49,177
Because when you're actually enjoying something, you are, in that moment, perfectly happy.

167
00:15:49,197 --> 00:15:55,082
I mean, when you get lost in a DVD, that's heaven, isn't it?

168
00:15:55,102 --> 00:16:01,490
You know, when you're eating your tiramisu, it's heaven, isn't it?

169
00:16:01,509 --> 00:16:07,056
You see, the actual indulgence doesn't present you with a problem, see?

170
00:16:07,947 --> 00:16:17,764
So when you're in love, when you're in a beautiful relationship, when you're out in the country, when you're listening to music, all that is wonderful.

171
00:16:19,186 --> 00:16:22,832
What we don't realize is that we formed a certain relationship to it.

172
00:16:23,933 --> 00:16:27,039
And that relationship is becoming a sort of dependency.

173
00:16:27,821 --> 00:16:33,009
And we're describing, unwittingly, happiness being an emotional state.

174
00:16:34,643 --> 00:16:38,147
Happiness is an emotional state.

175
00:16:38,586 --> 00:16:43,192
And this emotional state is dependent on something outside me over which I don't have control.

176
00:16:45,474 --> 00:16:48,596
You see, the DVD doesn't get posted.

177
00:16:49,758 --> 00:16:50,798
The friend dies.

178
00:16:50,840 --> 00:16:55,043
The person I love most disappears and hates me.

179
00:16:55,865 --> 00:16:57,485
I mean, you know, like, yeah, see?

180
00:16:58,246 --> 00:17:04,093
And then you realize that maybe there's a different way of relating to what is beautiful in life.

181
00:17:05,086 --> 00:17:07,630
Hmm, that's a difficult one.

182
00:17:07,650 --> 00:17:15,501
But we don't start really seeking that new relationship until we see the aftermath of indulgence.

183
00:17:15,521 --> 00:17:18,045
And the aftermath of indulgence is dependency.

184
00:17:18,605 --> 00:17:22,491
Some sort of psychological dependency on something.

185
00:17:22,752 --> 00:17:25,517
Even if it's, you know, just taking a walk in the country.

186
00:17:25,777 --> 00:17:29,321
It can be something very simple, but if you don't get it, then you feel that lack.

187
00:17:30,825 --> 00:17:30,904
Hmm?

188
00:17:30,924 --> 00:17:33,087
There's a frustration when we don't get what we want.

189
00:17:34,250 --> 00:17:34,349
Yeah?

190
00:17:34,971 --> 00:17:36,294
There's grief when you lose it.

191
00:17:37,796 --> 00:17:48,170
There's a constant sense of anxiety which we very rarely acknowledge which is always that knowledge that there is a possibility of losing it.

192
00:17:48,609 --> 00:17:52,635
That's why we have this huge insurance industry.

193
00:17:52,655 --> 00:17:59,204
And then finally, something that our society won't link with indulgence is boredom.

194
00:18:00,385 --> 00:18:03,830
And boredom is the psychological driver

195
00:18:04,402 --> 00:18:10,326
for all our commercialism, for all our consumerism, is boredom.

196
00:18:10,346 --> 00:18:19,276
I mean, I know that they put these adverts out and they blame the adverts and they blame all this clever stuff, but actually, psychologically, it's the inability to be with boredom.

197
00:18:20,396 --> 00:18:21,897
Boredom seeks distraction.

198
00:18:22,238 --> 00:18:24,140
So you don't have to advertise very much.

199
00:18:25,521 --> 00:18:27,583
As soon as somebody's bored, they're going to seek distraction.

200
00:18:28,124 --> 00:18:33,648
You just put something in their way, you know, cost of coffee, doesn't matter what it is, you just start and you've got to go in there.

201
00:18:33,898 --> 00:18:35,461
and get out of this state of boredom.

202
00:18:37,202 --> 00:18:42,008
Remember that after the Buddha was fully liberated, Mara sent his three daughters.

203
00:18:43,189 --> 00:18:48,074
There was sensual pleasure, sexual pleasure and boredom.

204
00:18:49,195 --> 00:18:51,657
It comes with that indulgence.

205
00:18:52,778 --> 00:19:02,589
And what that little myth tells us is that even though the Buddha was liberated on that night, there were still these leftover conditionings.

206
00:19:02,941 --> 00:19:04,722
which took seven years to burn out.

207
00:19:06,364 --> 00:19:08,967
So finally it took seven years.

208
00:19:08,987 --> 00:19:13,330
So really catching that in our lives, you see.

209
00:19:13,371 --> 00:19:19,076
Now what happens is, I think, is that when you do that, you become afraid.

210
00:19:19,317 --> 00:19:25,521
There's a possibility that one becomes afraid or averse to pleasure because you see the aftermath suffering.

211
00:19:26,983 --> 00:19:30,326
And this is often a big mistake for monastics, actually.

212
00:19:30,567 --> 00:19:32,509
That's why you can't laugh in a monastery.

213
00:19:33,619 --> 00:19:34,560
There's no humor.

214
00:19:34,621 --> 00:19:35,521
You don't crack a joke.

215
00:19:36,742 --> 00:19:41,626
So you have to be careful that you don't get this idea that you have to get rid of pleasure.

